Robberies are down 13% over the last 12 months compared to the average from 2019-2021.

The city averaged 144 robberies a week since last May. In 2019, that number was 177 a week.

The risk is not the same neighborhood to neighborhood.

About 82% of city residents live in neighborhoods where the robbery rate over the last 12 months is down or about the same as the three-year average. About 2% live in neighborhoods where the robbery rate is up more than 20%.

ABC13s data team looked at the Houston Police Departments data by neighborhood from 2019 through last month.

A closer look at Houston robberies neighborhood by neighborhood

The map color-codes each neighborhood by the robbery rate over the last 12 months, through the end of April, which is the most recent comprehensive data released by the Houston Police Department.

The yellow areas are neighborhoods where the robbery rate is among the 25% highest rates in the city.

Click on any neighborhood on the map to see detailed figures, rates and trends. You can also search for a street name, place, landmark or zip code.



About 15% of Houston residents now live in neighborhoods where there was at least one robbery every month over the last year. Heres a look at robberies citywide every month since 2019.
